The functions we need to time events are part of C's standard library, and are accessed through the statement: \\texttt{\\#include \\textless time.h\\textgreater}. There are actually two different methods for timing events in C. Figure~\\ref{fig:timing_methods} shows the major differences between these two methods.

Method 1 uses \\texttt{clock} to time events. This function gives the amount of processor time that has elapsed since the program began running. To time an event we use \\texttt{clock} twice, once at the start of the event and once at the end. The time is returned as a built-in type, \\texttt{clock\\_t}. The total time required by an event is its start time subtracted from its stop time. Since this result could be any legitimate numeric type, we \\textbf{type cast} it to

