Figure~\\ref{fig:stack-call} meets the requirements of our application.

\\begin{verbatim}
Stack CreateS(max-stack-size) ::=

#define MAX_STACK_SIZE 100 /*maximum stack size*/
typedef struct {
    int key;
    /* other fields */
} element;
element stack[MAX_STACK_SIZE];
int top = -1;
Boolean IsEmpty(Stack) ::= top < 0;
\\end{verbatim}

\\begin{verbatim}
Boolean IsFull(Stack) ::= top >= MAX_STACK_SIZE-1;
\\end{verbatim}

The \\texttt{IsEmpty} and \\texttt{IsFull} operations are simple, and we will implement them directly in the \\texttt{add} (Program~\\ref{prog:add}) and \\texttt{delete} (Program~\\ref{prog:delete}) functions. In each of these functions we have passed in the top of the stack as a parameter. The stack is kept global and ``hidden'' because we want to reinforce the concept that the only access to the stack is through the pointer to the top. The functions are short and require little explanation. Function \\texttt{add} checks to see if the stack is full. If it is, it calls \\texttt{stack-full}. Although we haven't implemented \\texttt{stack-full}, minimally it should print an error message to the standard error device (\\texttt{stderr}). If the stack is not full, we increment \\texttt{top} and add \\texttt{item} to the stack. Implementation of the delete operation parallels that of the add operation. For

