The representation of a queue in sequential locations is more difficult than that of the stack. The simplest scheme employs a one-dimensional array and two variables, \\textit{front} and \\textit{rear}. Given this representation, we can define the queue operations in Structure 3.2 as:

\\begin{verbatim}
Queue CreateQ(max_queue_size) ::=
#define MAX_QUEUE_SIZE 100 /*Maximum queue size*/
typedef struct {
    int key;
    /* other fields */
} element;
element queue[MAX_QUEUE_SIZE];
int rear = -1;
int front = -1;
Boolean IsEmptyQ(queue) ::= front == rear
\\end{verbatim}

\\documentclass{article}
\\usepackage{graphicx}
\\usepackage{amsmath}

\\begin{document}

\\section*{The Queue Abstract Data Type 109}

time-consuming, particularly when there are many elements in it. In fact, \\texttt{queue\\_full} has a worst case complexity of $O(\\texttt{MAX\\_QUEUE\\_SIZE})$. $\\Box$

We can obtain a more efficient queue representation if we regard the array \\texttt{queue[MAX\\_QUEUE\\_SIZE]} as circular. In this representation, we initialize \\texttt{front} and \\texttt{rear} to 0 rather than -1. The \\texttt{front} index always points one position counterclockwise from the first element in the queue. The \\texttt{rear} index points to the current end of the queue. The queue is empty iff \\texttt{front} = \\texttt{rear}. Figure 3.6 shows empty and nonempty circular queues for \\texttt{MAX\\_QUEUE\\_SIZE} = 6. Figure 3.7 illustrates two full queues for \\texttt{MAX\\_QUEUE\\_SIZE} = 6. While these have space for one more element, the addition of such an element will result in \\texttt{front} = \\texttt{rear} and we won't be able to distinguish between an empty and a full queue. So, we adopt the convention that a circular queue of size \\texttt{MAX\\_QUEUE\\_SIZE} will be permitted to hold at most \\texttt{MAX\\_QUEUE\\_SIZE} - 1 elements.

\\begin{figure}[h]
\\centering
\\includegraphics[width=0.8\\textwidth]{_page_0_Figure_3.jpeg}
\\caption{Empty and nonempty circular queues}
\\label{fig:3.6}
\\end{figure}

Implementing \\texttt{addq} and \\texttt{deleteq} for a circular queue is slightly more difficult since we must assure that a circular rotation occurs. This is attained by using the modulus operator. The circular rotation of the rear index in \\texttt{addq} (Program 3.5) occurs in the statement:

\\begin{verbatim}
*rear = (*rear + 1) % MAX_QUEUE_SIZE;
\\end{verbatim}

Notice that we rotate \\texttt{rear} before we place the item in \\texttt{queue[rear]}. Similarly, in \\texttt{deleteq} (Program 3.6), we rotate \\texttt{front} with the statement:

\\begin{verbatim}
*front = (*front + 1) % MAX_QUEUE_SIZE;
\\end{verbatim}

\\end{document}

\\section{110 Stacks And Queues}

\\begin{figure}[h]
\\centering
\\includegraphics[width=0.45\\textwidth]{_page_0_Figure_1.jpeg}
\\caption{Full circular queues}
\\end{figure}

and then we remove the item.

\\begin{verbatim}
void addq(int front, int *rear, element item)
{
    /* add an item to the queue */
    *rear = (*rear+1) % MAX_QUEUE_SIZE;
    if (front == *rear) {
        queue_full(rear); /* reset rear and print error*/
        return;
    }
    queue[*rear] = item;
}
\\end{verbatim}

\\textbf{Program 3.5:} Add to a circular queue

Observe that the test for a full queue in \\texttt{addq} and the test for an empty queue in \\texttt{deleteq} are the same. In the case of \\texttt{addq}, however, when \\texttt{front == *rear} is evaluated and found to be true, there is actually one space free (\\texttt{queue[rear]}) since the first element in the queue is not at \\texttt{queue[front]} but is one position clockwise from this point. As remarked earlier, if we insert an item here, then we will not be able to distinguish between the cases of full and empty, since the insertion would leave \\texttt{front} equal to \\texttt{rear}. To avoid this we signal \\texttt{queue\\_full}, thus permitting a maximum of \\texttt{MAX\\_QUEUE\\_SIZE} $-1$ rather than \\texttt{MAX\\_QUEUE\\_SIZE} elements in the queue at any time. We leave the implementation of \\texttt{queue\\_full} as an exercise.

