void add(int i, element item)
{
    /* add an item to the ith stack */
    if (top[i] == boundary[i+1])
        stack_full(i);
    memory[++top[i]] = item;
}
\\end{verbatim}

\\textbf{Program 3.12:} Add an \\textit{item} to the stack \\textit{stack\\_no}

The \\textit{add} (Program 3.12) and \\textit{delete} (Program 3.13) functions for multiple stacks appear to be as simple as those we used for the representation of a single stack. However, this is not really the case because the $top[i] == boundary[i+1]$ condition in \\textit{add} implies only that a particular stack ran out of memory, not that the entire memory is full. In fact, there may be a lot of unused space between other stacks in array \\textit{memory} (see Figure 3.19). Therefore, we create an error recovery function, $stack\\_full$, which determines if there is any free space in memory. If there is space available, it should shift the

\\section{Stacks And Queues}

stacks so that space is allocated to the full stack.

\\begin{verbatim}
element delete(int i)
{
  /* remove top element from the ith stack */
  if (top[i] == boundary[i])
    return stack_empty(i);
  return memory[top[i]--];
}
\\end{verbatim}

\\textbf{Program 3.13:} Delete an \\emph{item} from the stack \\emph{stack\\_no}

\\begin{figure}[h]
  \\centering
  \\includegraphics[width=\\textwidth]{_page_0_Figure_4.jpeg}
