There are several ways that we can design \\texttt{stack\\_full} so that we can add elements to this stack until the array is full. We outline one method here. Other methods are discussed in the exercises. We can guarantee that \\texttt{stack\\_full} adds elements as long as there is free space in array \\texttt{memory} if we:

\\begin{enumerate}
  \\item Determine the least, $j$, $stack\\_no < j < n$, such that there is free space between stacks $j$ and $j+1$. That is, $top[j] < boundary[j+1]$. If there is such a $j$, then move stacks $stack\\_no+1$, $stack\\_no+2$, $\\cdots$, $j$ one position to the right (treating $memory[0]$ as leftmost and $memory[MEMORY\\_SIZE-1]$ as rightmost). This creates a space between stacks $stack\\_no$ and $stack\\_no+1$.

  \\item If there is no $j$ as in (1), then look to the left of stack $stack\\_no$. Find the largest $j$ such that $0 \\le j < stack\\_no$ and there is space between stacks $j$ and $j+1$. That is, $top[j] < boundary[j+1]$. If there is such a $j$, then move stacks $j+1$, $j+2$, $\\cdots$, $stack\\_no$ one space to the left. This also creates a space between stacks $stack\\_no$ and $stack\\_no+1$.

  \\item If there is no $j$ satisfying either condition (1) or condition (2), then all $MEMORY\\_SIZE$ spaces of memory are utilized and there is no free space. In this case \\texttt{stack\\_full} terminates with an error message.
\\end{enumerate}

immediately after the \\texttt{printf} statement, then the pointer to the storage used to hold the value 3.14 has disappeared. Now there is no way to retrieve this storage. This is an example of a \\textit{dangling reference}. Whenever all pointers to a dynamically allocated area of storage are lost, the storage is lost to the program. As we examine programs that make use of pointers and dynamic storage, we will make it a point to always return storage after we no longer need it.

\\section{4.2 SINGLY LINKED LISTS}

Linked lists are drawn as an ordered sequence of nodes with links represented as arrows (Figure~\\ref{fig:linkedlist}). The name of the pointer to the first node in the list is the name of the list. Thus, the list of Figure~\\ref{fig:linkedlist} is called \\textit{ptr}. Notice that we do not explicitly put in the values of the pointers, but simply draw arrows to indicate that they are there. We do this to reinforce the facts that:

\\begin{enumerate}
    \\item the nodes do not reside in sequential locations
    \\item the locations of the nodes may change on different runs
\\end{enumerate}

When we write a program that works with lists, we almost never look for a specific address except when we test for the end of the list.

\\begin{figure}[h]
    \\centering
    \\includegraphics[width=0.8\\textwidth]{_page_0_Figure_7.jpeg}
    \\caption{Usual way to draw a linked list}
    \\label{fig:linkedlist}
\\end{figure}

Let us now see why it is easier to make arbitrary insertions and deletions using a linked list rather than a sequential list. To insert the word \\textit{mat} between \\textit{cat} and \\textit{sat}, we must:

\\begin{enumerate}
    \\item Get a node that is currently unused; let its address be \\textit{paddr}.
    \\item Set the data field of this node to \\textit{mat}.
    \\item Set \\textit{paddr}'s link field to point to the address found in the link field of the node containing \\textit{cat}.
    \\item Set the link field of the node containing \\textit{cat} to point to \\textit{paddr}.
\\end{enumerate}

\\subsection{Lists}

Figure~4.2 shows how the list changes after we insert \\texttt{mat}. The dashed line out of the node containing \\texttt{cat} is the old link, while the solid line shows the new link. Notice that when we insert \\texttt{mat} we do not move any elements that are already in the list. Thus, we have overcome the need to move data, but we have the additional storage needed for the link field. As we will see, this is not too severe a penalty.

\\begin{figure}[h]
\\centering
\\includegraphics[width=0.8\\textwidth]{_page_0_Picture_2.jpeg}
\\caption{Insert \\texttt{mat} after \\texttt{cat}}
\\label{fig:insert_mat}
\\end{figure}

Now suppose that we want to delete \\texttt{mat} from the list. We only need to find the element that immediately precedes \\texttt{mat}, which is \\texttt{cat}, and set its link field to point to \\texttt{mat}'s link field (Figure~4.3). We have not moved any data, and although the link field of \\texttt{mat} still points to \\texttt{sat}, \\texttt{mat} is no longer in the list.

\\begin{figure}[h]
