From this brief discussion of linked lists, we see that we need the following capabilities to make linked representations possible:

\\begin{enumerate}
    \\item A mechanism for defining a node's structure, that is, the fields it contains. We use \\textit{self-referential structures}, discussed in Section~2.2, to do this.
    \\item A way to create new nodes when we need them. The \\texttt{malloc} function handles this operation.
    \\item A way to remove nodes that we no longer need. The \\texttt{free} function handles this operation.
\\end{enumerate}

We will present several small examples to show how to create and use linked lists in C.

\\textbf{Example 4.1} [\\textit{List of words ending in at}]: To create a linked list of words, we first define a node structure for the list. This structure specifies the type of each of the fields.

To place the word \\textit{bat} into our list we use the statements:
\\begin{verbatim}
strcpy(ptr->data, "bat");
ptr->link = NULL;
\\end{verbatim}
These statements create the list illustrated in Figure 4.4. Notice that the node has a null link field because there is no next node in the list.

\\begin{figure}[h]
\\centering
\\includegraphics[width=0.5\\textwidth]{_page_0_Picture_4.jpeg}
\\caption{Referencing the fields of a node}
\\label{fig:4.4}
\\end{figure}

\\textbf{Example 4.2 [Two-node linked list]:} We want to create a linked list of integers. The node structure is defined as:
\\begin{verbatim}
typedef struct list-node *list-pointer;
struct list-node {
    int data;
    list-pointer link;
};
list-pointer ptr = NULL;
\\end{verbatim}
A linked list with two nodes is created by function \\textit{create2} (Program 4.2). We set the data field of the first node to 10 and that of the second to 20. The variable \\textit{first} is a pointer to the first node; \\textit{second} is a pointer to the second node. Notice that the link field of the first node is set to point to the second node, while the link field of the second node is \\texttt{NULL}. The variable \\textit{first}, which is the pointer to the start of the list, is returned by \\textit{create2}. Figure 4.5 shows the resulting list structure.

\\textbf{Example 4.3 [List insertion]:} Let \\textit{ptr} be a pointer to a linked list as in Example 4.2. Assume that we want to insert a node with a data field of 50 after some arbitrary node. Function \\textit{insert} (Program 4.3) accomplishes this task. In this function, we pass in two pointer variables. The first variable, \\textit{ptr}, is the pointer to the first node in the list. If this variable contains a null address (i.e., there are no nodes in the list), we want to change \\textit{ptr} so that it points to the node with 50 in its data field. This means that we must pass in the address of \\textit{ptr}. This is why we use the declaration \\texttt{list-pointer *ptr}. Since the address of the second pointer, \\textit{node}, does not change, we do not need to pass in its address as a parameter. A typical function call would be \\texttt{insert(\\&ptr, node)}; where \\textit{ptr} points to the start of the list and \\textit{node} points to the new node.

\\begin{verbatim}
list-pointer create2()
{
    /* create a linked list with two nodes */
    list-pointer first, second;
    first = (list-pointer)malloc(sizeof(list-node));
    second = (list-pointer)malloc(sizeof(list-node));
    second->link = NULL;
    second->data = 20;
    first->data = 10;
    first->link = second;
    return first;
}
\\end{verbatim}

