Using our genealogical charts as examples, let us define formally what we mean by a tree.

\\textbf{Definition:} A \\emph{tree} is a finite set of one or more nodes such that:
\\begin{enumerate}
    \\item There is a specially designated node called the \\emph{root}.
    \\item The remaining nodes are partitioned into $n \\ge 0$ disjoint sets $T_1, \\dots, T_n$, where each of these sets is a tree. We call $T_1, \\dots, T_n$ the subtrees of the root. $\\square$
\\end{enumerate}

Notice that we have an instance of a recursive definition since we define the subtrees as trees. If we return to Figure~\\ref{fig:genealogical_charts}, we see that the root of tree (a) is Dusty, while that of tree (b) is Proto Indo-European. Tree (a) has two subtrees whose roots are Honey Bear and Brandy, while tree (b) has three subtrees with roots, Italic, Hellenic, and Germanic. Since $T_1, \\dots, T_n$ must be disjoint sets, we prohibit subtrees from ever connecting together, that is, we forbid crossbreeding. Our definition also indicates that every node in the tree is the root of some subtree. For instance, West Germanic is the root of a subtree of Germanic, and it has three subtrees with the following roots: Low German, High German, and Yiddish.

