\\section*{188 Trees}

There are many terms that we use when referring to trees. A \\emph{node} stands for the item of information and the branches to other nodes. For example, the tree in Figure~\\ref{fig:sample_tree} has 13 nodes, with each item of information represented as a letter for convenience. The root of the tree is A. Normally we draw trees with the root at the top.

\\begin{figure}[htbp]
\\centering
\\includegraphics[width=0.6\\textwidth]{_page_0_Figure_2.jpeg}
\\caption{A sample tree}
\\label{fig:sample_tree}
\\end{figure}

The \\emph{degree} of a node is the number of subtrees of the node. For example, the degree of A is 3, of C is 1, and of F is zero. The \\emph{degree of a tree} is the maximum degree of the nodes in the tree. For example, the tree of Figure~\\ref{fig:sample_tree} has degree 3. A node with degree zero is a \\emph{leaf} or \\emph{terminal} node. For instance, K, L, F, G, M, I, and J are all leaf nodes.

A node that has subtrees is the \\emph{parent} of the roots of the subtrees, and the roots of the subtrees are the \\emph{children} of the node. For instance, node B is the parent of nodes E and F, which conversely are the children of B. Children of the same parent are \\emph{siblings}. For instance, H, I, and J are siblings. We can extend this familial terminology to grandparents and grandchildren. Thus, we can say that D is the grandparent of M, and A is the grandparent of E, F, G, H, I, and J. The \\emph{ancestors} of a node are all the nodes along the path from the root to the node. For example, the ancestors of M are A, D, and H. Conversely, the \\emph{descendants} of a node are all the nodes that are in its subtrees. For example, E, F, K, and L are the descendants of B.

