\\subsection{5.2.3 Binary Tree Representations}

\\subsubsection{Array Representation}
The numbering scheme used in Figure~\\ref{fig:5.10} suggests our first representation of a binary tree in memory. Since the nodes are numbered from 1 to $n$, we can use a one-dimensional array to store the nodes. (We do not use the 0th position of the array.) Using Lemma~\\ref{lem:5.3} we can easily determine the locations of the parent, left child, and right child of any node, $i$, in the binary tree.

\\begin{lemma}\\label{lem:5.3}
If a complete binary tree with $n$ nodes (depth = $\\lfloor \\log_2 n + 1 \\rfloor$) is represented sequentially, then for any node with index $i$, $1 \\leq i \\leq n$, we have:
\\begin{enumerate}
    \\item $parent(i)$ is at $\\lfloor i / 2 \\rfloor$ if $i \\neq 1$. If $i = 1$, $i$ is at the root and has no parent.
    \\item $left\\text{-}child(i)$ is at $2i$ if $2i \\leq n$. If $2i > n$, then $i$ has no left child.
    \\item $right\\text{-}child(i)$ is at $2i + 1$ if $2i + 1 \\leq n$. If $2i + 1 > n$, then $i$ has no right child.
\\end{enumerate}
\\end{lemma}

\\textbf{Proof:} We prove (2). (3) is an immediate consequence of (2) and the numbering of nodes on the same level from left to right. (1) follows from (2) and (3). We prove (2) by induction on $i$. For $i = 1$, clearly the left child is at 2 unless $2 > n$, in which case $i$ has no

