\\subsection{Searching A Binary Search Tree}

Since the definition of a binary search tree is recursive, it is easiest to describe a recursive search method. Suppose we wish to search for an element with a \\textit{key}. We begin at the \\textit{root}. If the \\textit{root} is \\texttt{NULL}, the search tree contains no elements and the search is unsuccessful. Otherwise, we compare \\textit{key} with the key value in \\textit{root}. If \\textit{key} equals \\textit{root}'s key value, then the search terminates successfully. If \\textit{key} is less than \\textit{root}'s key value, then no element in the right subtree can have a key value equal to \\textit{key}. Therefore, we search the left subtree of \\textit{root}. If \\textit{key} is larger than \\textit{root}'s key value, we search the right subtree of \\textit{root}. The function \\texttt{search} (Program~\\ref{prog:search}) recursively searches the subtrees.

\\begin{verbatim}
tree_pointer search(tree_pointer root, int key)
{
    /* return a pointer to the node that contains key. If
       there is no such node, return NULL. */
    if (!root) return NULL;
    if (key == root->data) return root;
    if (key < root->data)
        return search(root->left_child, key);
    return search(root->right_child, key);
}
\\end{verbatim}

\\textbf{Program 5.15:} Recursive search of a binary search tree

We can easily replace the recursive search function with a comparable iterative one. The function *search!* (Program 5.16) accomplishes this by replacing the recursion with a **while** loop.
``` return a pointer to the node that contains key. If tree—pointer search2{tree—pointer tree, int key) there is no such node, return NULL.
while (tree) { if (key == tree->data) return tree;
if (key tree else tree tree->data) tree->left—child;
tree->right—child;
return NULL;
```
