    \\item has root equal to root $(T_1)$; has left subtree equal to $B(T_{11}, T_{12}, \\dots, T_{1m})$, where $T_{11}, T_{12}, \\dots, T_{1m}$ are the subtrees of root $(T_1)$; and has right subtree $B(T_2, \\dots, T_n)$
\\end{enumerate}

\\subsection{Forest Traversals}

Preorder, inorder, and postorder traversals of the corresponding binary tree $T$ of a forest $F$ have a natural correspondence with traversals of $F$. The preorder traversal of $T$ is equivalent to visiting the nodes of $F$ in tree preorder. We define this as:

\\begin{enumerate}
    \\item If $F$ is empty, then return.
    \\item Visit the root of the first tree of $F$.
    \\item Traverse the subtrees of the first tree in tree preorder.
    \\item Traverse the remaining trees of $F$ in preorder.
\\end{enumerate}

Inorder traversal of $T$ is equivalent to visiting the nodes of $F$ in tree inorder, which is defined as:

\\begin{enumerate}
    \\item If $F$ is empty, then return.
\\end{enumerate}

