This walk does not cross all bridges exactly once, nor does it return to the starting land area $B$. We invite you to try to find a solution to the problem. You should discover quickly, as did Euler, that the people of Koenigsberg cannot walk across each bridge exactly once and return to their starting location. Euler solved the problem by using a graph (actually a multigraph) in which the land areas are vertices and the bridges are edges. His solution is not only elegant, it applies to all graphs.

\\begin{figure}[h]
