The function \\texttt{allcosts} (Program 6.12) computes $A^{n-1}[i][j]$. The computations are done in place using the array \\texttt{distance}, which we define as:
\\begin{verbatim}
int distance[MAX_VERTICES][MAX_VERTICES];
\\end{verbatim}

The reason this computation can be carried out in place is that $A^k[i,k] = A^{k-1}[i,k]$ and $A^k[k,j] = A^{k-1}[k,j]$ and so the in place computation does not alter the outcome.

\\textbf{Analysis of \\texttt{allcosts}:} This algorithm is especially easy to analyze because the looping is independent of the data in the distance matrix. The total time for \\texttt{allcosts} is $O(n^3)$. An exercise examines the extensions needed to generate the $\\langle i, j \\rangle$ paths with these lengths. We can speed up the algorithm by using our knowledge of the fact that the innermost \\texttt{for}

\\begin{verbatim}
void allcosts(int cost[][MAX_VERTICES], int distance[][MAX_VERTICES], int n)
{
    /* determine the distances from each vertex to every other vertex,
       cost is the adjacency matrix, distance is the matrix of distances */
    int i, j, k;
    for (i = 0; i < n; i++)
        for (j = 0; j < n; j++)
            distance[i][j] = cost[i][j];
    for (k = 0; k < n; k++)
        for (i = 0; i < n; i++)
            for (j = 0; j < n; j++)
                if (distance[i][k] + distance[k][j] < distance[i][j])
                    distance[i][j] = distance[i][k] + distance[k][j];
}
\\end{verbatim}

Program 6.12: All pairs, shortest paths function

loop is executed only when $distance[i][k]$ and $distance[k][j]$ are not equal to $\\infty$.

Example 6.6: Using the graph of Figure 6.33(a), we obtain the cost matrix of Figure 6.33(b). Figure 6.34 shows the initial matrix, $A^{-1}$, and matrices $A^0$, $A^1$, $A^2$.

We can easily find $A^+$ by using \\texttt{allcosts}. We first modify \\texttt{cost} so that $\\texttt{cost}[i][j] = 1$ if $\\langle i, j \\rangle$ is an edge in $G$ and $\\texttt{cost}[i][j] = +\\infty$ if $\\langle i, j \\rangle$ is not in $G$. When \\texttt{allcosts} terminates, we obtain $A^+$ from \\texttt{distance} by letting $A^+[i][j] = 1$ iff $\\texttt{distance}[i][j] < +\\infty$. We then obtain $A^*$ by setting all the diagonal elements in $A^+$ to 1. The total time is $O(n^3)$. We can simplify the algorithm by changing the \\texttt{if} statement in the nested \\texttt{for} loops to:
\\[
\\texttt{distance}[i][j] = \\texttt{distance}[i][j] \\mid \\texttt{distance}[i][k] \\&\\& \\texttt{distance}[k][j]
\\]
and initializing \\texttt{distance} to be the adjacency matrix of the graph. With this modification, \\texttt{distance} will be equivalent to $A^+$ when \\texttt{allcosts} terminates. For an undirected graph, the (reflexive) transitive closure matrix may be computed in $O(n^2)$ time by first computing the connected components.

