Lemma 7.1: Let $T_{avg}(n)$ be the expected time for quicksort to sort a file with $n$ records. Then there exists a constant $k$ such that $T_{avg}(n) \\le kn \\log_e n$ for $n \\ge 2$.

Proof: In the call to quicksort $(0, n-1)$, $K_0$ gets placed at position $j$. This leaves us with the problem of sorting two subfiles of size $j$ and $n-j-1$, respectively. The expected time for this is $T_{avg}(j) + T_{avg}(n-j-1)$. The remainder of the algorithm clearly takes at most $cn$ time for some constant $c$. Since $j$ may take on any of the values $0$ to $n-1$ with equal probability we have
\\begin{equation}
T_{avg}(n) \\le cn + \\frac{1}{n} \\sum_{j=0}^{n-1} (T_{avg}(j) + T_{avg}(n-j-1)) = cn + \\frac{2}{n} \\sum_{j=0}^{n-1} T_{avg}(j), \\quad n \\ge 2
\\tag{7.1}
\\end{equation}

We may assume $T_{avg}(0) \\le b$ and $T_{avg}(1) \\le b$ for some constant $b$. We shall now show $T_{avg}(n) \\le kn \\log_e n$ for $n \\ge 2$ and $k = 2(b + c)$. The proof is by induction on $n$.

Induction Base: For $n = 2$ we have from Eq. (7.1)
\\begin{equation}
T_{avg}(2) \\le 2c + 2b \\le kn \\log_e 2
\\end{equation}

Induction Hypothesis: Assume $T_{avg}(n) \\le kn \\log_e n$ for $1 \\le n < m$

Induction Step: From Eq. (7.1) and the induction hypothesis we have
\\begin{equation}
T_{avg}(m) \\le cm + \\frac{4b}{m} + \\frac{2}{m} \\sum_{j=2}^{m-1} T_{avg}(j) \\le cm + \\frac{4b}{m} + \\frac{2k}{m} \\sum_{j=2}^{m-1} j \\log_e j
\\tag{7.2}
\\end{equation}

