We assume that \\texttt{list[i].link} and \\texttt{list[i].key} refer to the \\texttt{link} and \\texttt{key} fields in record $i$, $0 \\le i \\le n-1$. Notice that we are implementing the \\texttt{link} field as an integer rather than a dynamic pointer. Initially \\texttt{list[i].link = -1}, which means that each record is in a chain that contains only itself. The function \\texttt{rmerge} (Program 7.11) implements the recursive merge sort; \\texttt{rmerge} returns an integer that points to the start of the sorted list. Most of the actual merging is accomplished through \\texttt{listmerge} (Program 7.12). This function takes two sorted chains, \\texttt{first} and \\texttt{second}, and returns an integer that points to the start of a new sorted chain that includes the first and second chains. Unlike the iterative implementation, the recursive one does not physically rearrange the list. Should this be necessary, we could use one of the schemes discussed in Section 7.9. The function call is \\texttt{start = rmerge(list, 0, n-1);}

\\textbf{Analysis of \\texttt{rmerge}:} One may readily verify that this linked version of merge sort results in a stable sorting function, and that its computing time is $O(n \\log n)$.

\\textbf{Example 7.6:} The input list is $(26, 5, 77, 1, 61, 11, 59, 15, 48, 19)$. At each recursive call, the current list that is indexed from left to right is divided into two sublists that are indexed from $\\lfloor (left + right)/2 \\rfloor$ and from $\\lfloor (left + right)/2 \\rfloor + 1$ to right,

\\begin{verbatim}
int rmerge(element list[], int lower, int upper)
/* sort the list, list[lower],..., list[upper]. The link
field in each record is initially set to -1. */
{
    int middle;
    if (lower >= upper)
        return lower;
    else {
        middle = (lower + upper) / 2;
        return listmerge(list, rmerge(list, lower, middle),
                        rmerge(list, middle + 1, upper));
    }
}
\\end{verbatim}

