\\section{9.2 DEAPS}
\\subsection{Definition}
A \\emph{deap} is a double-ended heap that supports the double-ended priority queue operations of insert, delete min, and delete max. As in the case of the min-max heap, these operations take logarithmic time on a deap. However, the deap is faster by a constant factor and the algorithms are simpler.

\\textbf{Definition:} A \\emph{deap} is a complete binary tree that is either empty or satisfies the following properties:
\\begin{enumerate}
    \\item The root contains no element.
    \\item The left subtree is a min-heap.
    \\item The right subtree is a max-heap.
    \\item If the right subtree is not empty, then let $i$ be any node in the left subtree. Let $j$ be the corresponding node in the right subtree. If such a $j$ does not exist, then let $j$ be the node in the right subtree that corresponds to the parent of $i$. The key in node $i$ is less than or equal to the key in $j$.
\\end{enumerate}

An example of an 11-element deap is shown in Figure 9.6. The root of the min-heap contains 5, while that of the max-heap contains 45. The min-heap node with key 10 corresponds to the max-heap node with key 25, while the min-heap node with key 15 corresponds to the max-heap node with key 20. For the node containing 9, the node $j$ defined in property (4) of the deap definition is the max-heap node that contains 40.

