(2) \\texttt{min\\_partner}(n). This function computes the min-heap node that corresponds to the max-heap position $n$. This is given by $n - 2^{\\lfloor \\log_2 n \\rfloor - 1}$.

(3) \\texttt{max\\_partner}(n). This function computes the max-heap node that corresponds to the parent of the min-heap position $n$. This is given by $(n + 2^{\\lfloor \\log_2 n \\rfloor - 1}) / 2$.

(4) \\texttt{min\\_insert} and \\texttt{max\\_insert}. These functions insert an element into a specified position of a min- and max-heap, respectively. This is done by following the path from this position toward the root of the respective heap. Elements are moved down as necessary until the correct place to insert the new element is found. This process differs from that used in Chapter 5 to insert into a min- or max-heap only in that the root is now at position 2 or 3 rather than at 1.

\\textbf{Analysis of \\texttt{deap\\_insert}:} The correctness of this function is easily established. Its complexity is $O(\\log n)$ as the height of the deap is $O(\\log n)$. $\\square$

