From Eq. (10.2) it is clear that $c_{ij}$ is minimal only if $\\text{cost}(L) = c_{i,k-1}$ and $\\text{cost}(R) = c_{k,j}$. Otherwise we could replace either $L$ or $R$ with a subtree of lower cost and thus obtain a binary search tree for $a_{i+1}, \\ldots, a_j$ with a lower cost than $c_{ij}$. This violates the assumption that $T_{ij}$ is optimal. Hence, Eq. (10.2) becomes:
\\begin{align}
c_{ij} &= p_k + c_{i,k-1} + c_{k,j} + w_{i,k-1} + w_{k,j} \\\\
&= w_{i,j} + c_{i,k-1} + c_{k,j}
\\tag{10.3}
\\end{align}
Since $T_{ij}$ is optimal, it follows from Eq. (10.3) that $r_{ij} = k$ is such that
\\begin{align}
w_{i,j} + c_{i,k-1} + c_{k,j} &= \\min_{i < l \\le j} \\{ w_{i,j} + c_{i,l-1} + c_{l,j} \\} \\\\
\\text{or} \\quad c_{i,k-1} + c_{k,j} &= \\min_{i < l \\le j} \\{ c_{i,l-1} + c_{l,j} \\}
\\tag{10.4}
\\end{align}
Equation (10.4) shows us how to obtain $T_{on}$ and $c_{on}$, starting from the knowledge that $T_{ii} = \\emptyset$ and $c_{ii} = 0$.

