Program 10.6 summarizes the steps involved in deletion from a leaf node $p$ of a 2-3 tree $t$.

There are three cases for a rotation depending on whether $p$ is the left, middle, or right child of its parent $r$. If $p$ is the left child of $r$, then let $q$ be the right sibling of $p$. Otherwise, let $q$ be the left sibling of $p$. Note that regardless of whether $r$ is a 2-node or a 3-node, $q$ is well defined. The three rotation cases are shown pictorially in Figure 10.18. A ``?'' denotes a don't care situation. $a$, $b$, $c$, and $d$ denote the children (i.e., roots of subtrees) of nodes.

Figure 10.19 shows the two cases for a combine when $p$ is the left child of $r$. We leave it as an exercise to obtain the figures for the cases when $p$ is a middle child and when $p$ is a right child.

The refinement of step 1 of Program 10.6 into C code is shown in Program 10.7. Programs 10.8 and 10.9 show the code for the rotate and combine operations when $p$ is the left child of $r$. We leave the development of the complete deletion function as an exercise.

