\\textbf{Lemma 10.2:} Consider a binary search that has $n$ elements / nodes. The amortized cost of a splay operation that begins at node $q$ is at most $3(\\log_2 n - r(q)) + 1$.

\\textbf{Proof:} Consider the three steps in the definition of a splay.

(1) In this step, $q$ is either \\texttt{NULL} or is the root. This step does not alter the potential of the tree. So its amortized and actual costs are the same. This cost is 1.

