\\section*{FUNDAMENTALS OF DATA STRUCTURES IN C}

Designed to function as a textbook or as a professional reference, \\textit{FUNDAMENTALS OF DATA STRUCTURES IN C} provides in-depth coverage of all aspects of data structure implementation in ANSI C. The book goes beyond the standard fare of Stacks, Queues, and Lists to offer such features as a full chapter on Search Structures and a discussion of Advanced Tree Structures. Recent data structure innovations rarely found in other texts are presented, including Fibonacci Heaps, Splay Trees, Red-Black Trees, 2-3 Trees, 2-3-4 Trees, Leftist Trees, Binokeal Heaps, Min-Max Heaps, and Deaps.

This comprehensive text on data structures and algorithms in the C language also offers:
\\begin{itemize}
    \\item balanced coverage of computer theory and hands-on computer programming
    \\item problem solving orientation encouraging the development of individual analytic talents
    \\item Over 400 exercises at all levels of difficulty, placed immediately after each section
    \\item A wealth of charts and illustrations for visual reinforcement of the principles of data structures
\\end{itemize}

\\section*{About the Authors}

\\textbf{Ellis Horowitz} is chair of the Computer Science Department and Professor of Computer Science and Electrical Engineering at the University of Southern California. Dr. Horowitz has published 30 proceedings, managed research grants totaling over \\$3.5 million, and has given nearly fifty presentations on a wide variety of computer science topics. He is the author of numerous articles and books, including six books for Computer Science Press (five co-written with Sartaj Sahni).

\\textbf{Sartaj Sahni} is Professor of Computer Science at the University of Florida and a Fellow of the IEEE. He received his B.Tech (Electrical Engineering) Degree from the Indian Institute of Technology, Kanpur, and his M.S. and Ph.D. in Computer Science from Cornell. Dr. Sahni has published over 140 articles and has written several texts. He is an editor of four professional journals and has managed over \\$8 million in research grants.

\\textbf{Susan Anderson-Freed} is chair of Illinois Wesleyan's Computer Science Department and a veteran of 14 years of teaching. She studied Computer Science at Bradley University, where she has been inducted into the University's Academic Hall of Fame, and received a Ph.D. from Indiana University.

